\begin{abstract}
We prove that (possibly charged) test fields satisfying the null energy condition {\em at the event horizon} cannot overspin/overcharge an extremal Kerr-Newman or Kerr-Newman-anti de Sitter black hole. This result is purely geometric and does not depend on the precise nature of the fields.
\end{abstract}








\section*{Introduction}

The weak cosmic censorship conjecture, advanced by Penrose in 1960 \cite{P69, W97}, forbids generic naked singularities to be visible from future null infinity. Among various pieces of circumstantial evidence supporting this conjecture, there are various results showing that it is impossible to overspin/overcharge an extremal Kerr-Newman black hole using test particles \cite{W74, TdFC76, Needham80} or test fields \cite{Semiz11, Toth12, DS13, Duztas14, Duztas15, Toth15}. This discussion has been extended to higher dimensions \cite{BCNR10}, to the case when there is a negative cosmological constant \cite{GL15, RS14}, and even to nearly extremal black holes \cite{Hubeny99, MS07, Hod08, JS09, SS11}.

In this paper, we prove that (possibly charged) test fields satisfying the null energy condition {\em at the event horizon} cannot overspin/overcharge an extremal Kerr-Newman or Kerr-Newman-anti de Sitter black hole. This is done by first establishing that the second law of black hole thermodynamics holds when considering such test fields, and then showing that this law, together with the Smarr formula and the first law, it implies the result. The argument is therefore purely geometric, and does not depend on the precise nature of the test fields.

We follow the conventions of \cite{MTW73, W84}; in particular, we use a system of units for which $c=G=1$.




